That was a lot _shorter_ than the <a href='#recipe-pan-roasting-chicken'>chicken instructions</a>, wasn't it? That's because we _spent the time_ to _understand_ the _cooking method_ of _pan-roasting_, rather than simply following a recipe. And once we've _learned_ something, it begins to _apply_ in ways we _hadn't anticipated_.

When we _follow directions_, we can expect to reach a _specific goal_. But when we _develop skills_, we're _capable_ and _prepared_ for _adaptation_ and _creativity_. If I asked you to _pan-roast salmon_ or _cauliflower_, to add _cumin_ or _cilantro_, you'd _know how_. You might be _unsure_ of the _exact cooking times_, _when_ to _add_ the _spices_, or the _colour_ you're _looking for_. But you have the <e>essential skills</e>, which are _all you need_ to start incorporating _more ingredients_ and _flavours_.
